07984nam a22011055i 9783110732757DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107327577 a10.1515/97831107327572doi  a(DE-B1597)574257  a(OCoLC)1301547117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aNK1520b.F88 2022 7aBUS0430002bisacsh04a745.4223/eng/2022032804aThe Future of Luxury Brands :bArtification and Sustainability /ced. by Annamma Joy. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XIII, 298 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAdvance Praise for The Future of Luxury Brands: Artification and Sustainability -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tChapter 1 Artification and Sustainability: Foundational Pillars of the Luxury Worlds of Art, Fashion, and Wine -- tPart 1: Luxury in the Time of Covid-19 -- tChapter 2 Luxury Consumption and Covid-19 -- tPart 2: The Art World -- tChapter 3 Organizational Aesthetics as Exploring the Spiritual of the Social -- tChapter 4 Being at Burning Man: Fabulations and Provocations -- tChapter 5 Valued Belongings: Museums and the Luxury Art Market -- tChapter 6 Art and Aesthetics in the Future of Luxury -- tPart 3: The World of Fashion -- tChapter 7 Wearing the Writing on the Wall: Streetwear and Street Art -- tChapter 8 Seller and Consumer Activists in the World of Canadian Diamonds: A Case of Italian Political Consumerism -- tChapter 9 That’s So Trashy – Artification of Waste in the Luxury Fashion Industry -- tChapter 10 Luxury Resale Shaping the Future of Fashion -- tPart 4: Wine and Hospitality Services -- tChapter 11 Artification and Social Responsibility in the Context of Fine Wine: Opus One -- tChapter 12 Sustainable Transformative Wine Tourism: Applications in Experiential Educational Tourism -- tChapter 13 Wines and Subversive Art: A Conceptual Definition of Natural Wines -- tChapter 14 The Artification of Hospitality: Elevating Service to Luxury Status -- tList of Contributors -- tAbout the Editor -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concepts of artification and sustainability are now both at the heart of luxury brand marketing strategies; artification as an ongoing process of transformation in the world of art and sustainability as an indispensable response to the issues of our times. The Future of Luxury Brands examines three interrelated luxury-marketing segments—the art world, fashion and fine wines including hospitality services—through the dual lenses of sustainability and artification. From safeguarding human and natural resources to upholding labor rights and protecting the environment, sustainability has taken center stage in consumer consciousness, embodying both moral authority and sound business practices. At the same time, artification—the process by which non-art is reconceived as art—applies the cachet of art to business, affording commercial products the sacred status accorded to works of art. When commercial products enter the realm of aesthetic creation, artification and consumer engagement inevitably increases. This pioneering book examining artification and sustainability as strategic pillars of marketing strategies in the luxury industry will be essential reading for practitioners working in luxury product companies, as also students of luxury brand marketing.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLuxuriesxDesignxEnvironmental aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Marketing / General.2bisacsh  aArtification.  aBrand Management.  aLuxury Brand Marketing.  aLuxury Goods.  aSustainability.1 aArmano, Linda, econtribut